{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564480"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:14:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:14:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16983"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16983"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.06,0.03,0.08,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87104"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9673"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71362"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3295"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28931"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87104"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her breast cancer treatment. She has completed chemotherapy and radiotherapy six months ago post bilateral mastectomy and is now in remission. She has a history of major depressive disorder, well-controlled on sertraline. She takes tamoxifen as her only other regular medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring the consultation, she jokes about her mastectomy saying \u0027Well, at least now I save money on bras!\u0027 and \u0027Shopping is much easier when you only need one cup size.\u0027 Despite these light-hearted comments, she engages appropriately in discussion about her follow-up care and demonstrates good insight into her condition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ego defence mechanisms best describes this patient\u0027s psychological adaptation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Denial","Intellectualisation","Displacement","Reaction formation","Humour"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates the mature ego defence mechanism of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehumour\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient uses jokes about her mastectomy as a way to cope with a difficult situation while still maintaining awareness of her condition and engaging appropriately in her medical care. This represents a healthy psychological adaptation that allows her to deal with anxiety and difficult emotions while maintaining social connections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReaction formation\u003C/strong\u003E involves converting unacceptable thoughts or feelings into their opposite. This would be seen if the patient expressed excessive positivity about her mastectomy while completely denying any negative feelings, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDenial\u003C/strong\u003E involves refusing to acknowledge aspects of reality that are difficult to accept. While the patient makes light of her situation, she demonstrates good insight and engagement with her medical care, showing she has not denied her condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntellectualisation\u003C/strong\u003E involves dealing with emotional conflict by excessive use of abstract thinking or generalising. This would be seen if the patient focused solely on medical statistics or technical aspects of her treatment while avoiding emotional content.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisplacement\u003C/strong\u003E involves redirecting feelings or impulses from their original object to a less threatening target. This would be seen if the patient expressed anger towards unrelated situations or people rather than dealing with her feelings about her cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe use of humour as a defence mechanism is considered mature because it allows for acknowledgment of difficult realities while providing emotional distance and maintaining social connections. It differs from denial or avoidance because the underlying reality is still recognised and addressed appropriately.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Humour is a mature ego defence mechanism that allows individuals to cope with difficult situations by finding comic elements.","Ego defences should be distinguished from maladaptive coping mechanisms that may appear superficially similar.","The use of humour as a defence mechanism can be adaptive when it helps maintain relationships and reduce anxiety without causing harm."],"references":["Vaillant GE, Bond M, Vaillant CO. An empirically validated hierarchy of defense mechanisms. Archives of general psychiatry. 1986 Aug 1;43(8):786-94.","Sadock BJ, Sadock VA, Ruiz P. Kaplan and Sadock\u0027s comprehensive textbook of psychiatry. lippincott Williams \u0026 wilkins; 2017 May 11."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71362"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16983"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71362"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-26T11:22:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T11:22:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9673"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87104"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags",